SunsetDecoy

Target IP: 192.168.186.85

Scanning



There are only two ports on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with port 80.

Enumeration

From the nmap scan above, there is an interesting file called save.zip for the port 80 application.


Browsing to port 80 on a web-browser shows the webpage above. I downloaded this zip file on my local machine. When trying to extract the contents of this zip file, I was asked to enter the password.


I used zip2john to obtain the hash of this zip file. Then I cracked the password of this zip file using john. I obtained the password manuel for the zip file.


After extracting the files using the password above, I obtained a directory called etc with six files inside it as shown above.


I find the file shadow interesting as it contains password hashes of root and 296640a3b825115a47b68fc44501c828. I saved the hashes in a file called hash.


Then using john, I cracked the password of 296640a3b825115a47b68fc44501c828. Maybe we can spray this credential 296640a3b825115a47b68fc44501c828:server against the SSH application running on port 22.

Exploitation


And now I have a foothold on the machine as 296640a3b825115a47b68fc44501c828. When trying to use commands such as whoami output the rbash message. To bypass this, I used the command ssh 296640a3b825115a47b68fc44501c828@192.168.186.85 -t 'bash --noprofile'.

Privilege Escalation


The PATH evnironmental variable only points to the user's home. I used the command export PATH=$PATH:/usr/bin to fix this. Now I am able to perform commands on the machine.


There are interesting files in the directory such as the honeypot.decoy file. This file is owned by root, but we have execute permission over it.


Running strings on honeypot.decoy outputs the interesting strings above. It looks like a program that allows us to perform different tasks on the machine. The option 7 Leave a note. is interesting. From the picture above, it looks like vi is run using /usr/bin/vi /tmp/cmFuZG9tc2Zvc2FuZm9kYW52cw==. Maybe we can escape it and spawn a root shell? But I had no luck.


The option AV Scan sounds interesting too. After running this option on the target machine, I transferred pspy64 to the target machine to see if any scripts are run. And I found a script called script.sh gets executed, as shown above. But I did not have access to this script! Time to enumerate further.



Looks like host is running chrootkit 0.49 version and it is vulnerable.


The steps are shown above to escalate privileges from local to root. Apparently we need to create a file called update. I guess we can put our reverse shell script inside this new file as this file is executed as root.


Creating the update file with the reverse shell script. Then I started a listener on port 8445 on my local machine. After, I updated the update file to be executable and then ran honeypot.decoy option 5.


And I got my reverse shell connection as root as shown above on the right terminal.

Flags
